There are several weaknesses in your code:

    l_cur_query VARCHAR2(5000) := &#39;SELECT count(*) as noofrecords,&#39;
              || l_groupby_column
              || &#39; as groupbycolumn  from bi_request where &#39;
              || l_groupby_column
              || &#39; IS NOT NULL&#39;;

You missed the `&#39;GROUP BY &#39;||l_groupby_column` clause.

    TYPE rec_groupby_data IS TABLE OF bi_request%rowtype;

This would only work if you run `SELECT * FROM bi_request...`. However, the selected columns and data types are known only at run-time.

    OPEN cur_groupby_data FOR l_cur_query USING l_groupby_column;

You cannot bind column names(i.e. `USING l_groupby_column`). Apart from that you did not define any placeholder (e.g. `:b1`) in your query string.


    out_groupby_tab := return_groupby_param_arr(return_groupby_report());
    out_groupby_tab.DELETE;

Fairly useless to initialize a variable and immediately delete it afterwards.


    LOOP
        FETCH cur_groupby_data BULK COLLECT INTO l_cur_groupby_data
    
    END LOOP;

When you use `FETCH ... BULK COLLECT INTO ...` then there is nothing to loop. `BULK COLLECT` fetches all data at once into your variable. Either use `BULK COLLECT INTO` or `FETCH ... INTO ...` together with a loop.

Over all, if you like to run such dynamic SQL then you have to use [DBMS_SQL][1] package. 


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/database/121/ARPLS/d_sql.htm#ARPLS058

